h;||&mdash;||&mdash;||&mdash;\n| align=\"center\" |Missed playoffs\n|-class=\"sortbottom\"\n| align=\"left\" |'''Career'''\n| ||329||185||134||{{Winning percentage|185|134}}|| ||34||21||13||{{Winning percentage|21|13}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.australialivetv.com KG and the General]\n{{navboxes|list=\n{{Australia Men Basketball Squad 1980 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Australia Men Basketball Squad 1984 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Australia Men Basketball Squad 1988 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Australia Men Basketball Squad 1992 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Canberra Cannons 1983 NBL champions}}\n{{Canberra Cannons 1984 NBL champions}}\n{{Canberra Cannons 1988 NBL champions}}\n{{Adelaide 36ers 1998 NBL champions}}\n{{Adelaide 36ers 1998-99 NBL champions}}\n{{Adelaide 36ers 2001-02 NBL champions}}\n{{Adelaide 36ers coach navbox}}\n{{NBL Grand Final MVPs}}\n{{NBL Best Defensive Players}}\n{{NBL 20th Anniversary Team}}\n{{NBL 25th Anniversary Team}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smyth, Phil}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Adelaide 36ers players]]\n[[Category:Australian basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Australian men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 1980 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 1984 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 1992 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from South Australia]]\n[[Category:Canberra Cannons players]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:National Basketball League (Australia) coaches]]\n[[Category:Olympic basketball players of Australia]]\n[[Category:Point guards]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Australian Sports Medal]]\n[[Category:Sport Australia Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Adelaide]]\n[[Category:Sydney Kings players]]\n[[Category:1986 FIBA World Championship players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=May 2011}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Phil Smyth\n| image = \n| position = [[Point guard]]\n| height_cm = 183\n| weight_kg = 76\n| nationality = Australian\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1958|5|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]]\n| high_school = \n| college = \n| career_start = 1982\n| career_end = 1995\n| years1 = 1982\n| team1 = [[St Kilda Saints (NBL)|St Kilda Saints]]\n| years2 = 1983\u20131992\n| team2 = [[Canberra Cannons]]\n| years3 = 1993\u20131994\n| team3 = [[Adelaide 36ers]]\n| years4 = 1995\n| team4 = [[Sydney Kings]]\n| cyears1 = 1998\u20132008\n| cteam1 = Adelaide 36ers\n| highlights =\n'''As a player:'''\n* 4x [[NBL (Australia) Best Defensive Player|Defensive Player of the Year]] (1982, 1983, 1988, 1989)\n* 6x [[NBL (Australia) All NBL Teams|All NBL First Team]] (1982\u20131985, 1988, 1989)\n* 3x NBL champion (1983, 1984, 1988)\n* [[NBL (Australia) Most Valuable Player - Grand Final|NBL Grand Final MVP]] (1988)\n* [[Australian International Player of the Year|Gaze Medal]] winner (1988)\n* [[NBL (Australia) 20th Anniversary Team|NBL's 20th Anniversary Team]]\n* [[NBL (Australia) 25th Anniversary Team|NBL's 25th Anniversary Team]]\n'''As a coach:'''\n* 3x NBL champion (1998, 1999, 2002)\n}}\n\n'''Philip John Smyth''' <small>[[Order of Australia|AM]]</small> (born 11 May 1958)<ref>https://www.olympic.org/philip-smyth</ref> is an Australian former professional [[basketball]] player and coach. He won three [[National Basketball League (Australia)|National Basketball League]] (NBL) championships with the [[Canberra Cannons]] before going on to be a three-time championship-winning [[head coach]] of the NBL's [[Adelaide 36ers]]. Smyth was a four-time Olympian with the [[Australian national basketball team]].\n\n==Professional career==\nSmyth, an Adelaide junior, was already seen as one of Australia's best [[point guard]]s when the [[National Basketball League (Australia)|National Basketball League]] first started in 1979, yet it took him until 1982 to actually play in the league, despite having represented Australia at the [[1978 FIBA World Championship]] in the [[Philippines]] and at the [[1980 Summer Olympics]] in [[Moscow]].\n\nFor personal reasons, Smyth chose not to play in the NBL until 1982 and even then, while still living in Adelaide, he signed to play with the [[St Kilda Saints (NBL)|St Kilda Saints]], commuting between his home in Adelaide and [[Melbourne]] where the Saints were based. He only played for St Kilda for the [[1982 NBL season]], winning the [[NBL (Australia) Best Defensive Player|NBL's Defensive Player of the Year]] award and selection in the [[NBL (Australia) All NBL Teams|NBL's First Team]] in the process before signing with the [[Canberra Cannons]] from 1983. At this time he also moved from Adelaide to Canberra for what would prove to be 10 seasons in Australia's [[Canberra|capital city]]. During that time he enhanced his reputation as one of the best ever Australian basketball players and helped transform the Cannons into a championship winning team.\n\nCanberra won their first NBL Championship in 1983, Smyth's first season with the club. The Cannons defeated the defending champion [[West Adelaide Bearcats]] 75-73 in the grand final. They would go on to win the championship again in 1984, this time defeating the emerging [[Brisbane Bullets]] 84-82 in another closely fought grand final win. Smyth's play during this time was a major contributor to Canberra's success. He won his second consecutive Defensive Player of the Year award in 1983 and was also a member of the [[NBL (Australia) All NBL Teams|ALL NBL First team]] in 1983, 1984, 1985, 1988 and 1989.\n\nSmyth would win his 3rd NBL Championship when the Cannons defeated the [[North Melbourne Giants]] in the 1988 grand final series two games to one. He would also be named as the [[NBL (Australia) Most Valuable Player - Grand Final|Grand Final MVP]] in 1988. He narrowly missed out on a fourth NBL crown in 1989 when the Giants reversed the 1988 result by defeating Canberra two games to one.\n\nHe would play on with the Cannons until the end of the 1992 NBL season when he was lured back home to Adelaide to play for the Adelaide 36ers. Despite being in the twilight of his playing career, Smyth would again be a major contributor helping the generally under-performing 36ers get back into the playoffs. Smyth played two seasons for the 36ers and would lose his second and last NBL grand final series in 1994, again to the North Melbourne Giants who defeated Adelaide 2-0 in the championship series.\n\nAfter two season back home in Adelaide, Smyth had a falling out with 36ers coach [[Mike Dunlap]] who had a reputation for favouring the younger players. During 1994 Dunlap had even begun to start 3rd year player [[Brett Maher (basketball)|Brett Maher]] as the 36ers point guard and playing Smyth from the bench despite Smyth still being the starting point guard for the Australian Boomers (when Smyth questioned Dunlap on why he was benched, Dunlap told him that it was simply because he was old). This saw Smyth sign for the NBL's highest profile club, the [[Sydney Kings]] for the 1995 season where he linked with his former Canberra championship winning coach Bob Turner. In an injury interrupted season, Smyth played just 16 games for the Kings, who didn't make the playoffs. He retired from playing professional basketball after his season with the Kings.\n\nPhil Smyth played 356 games in his NBL career, 25 with St Kilda, 282 with Canberra, 33 for Adelaide and 16 for Sydney. He averaged 22.3 points per game at 44.8%, 5.3 rebounds, 5.5 assists and 2.8 steals.\n\n==International career==\nSmyth represented Australia at four [[Summer Olympic Games]] ([[Basketball at the 1980 Summer Olympics|1980]], [[Basketball at the 1984 Summer Olympics|1984]], [[Basketball at the 1988 Summer Olympics|1988]] and [[Basketball at the 1992 Summer Olympics|1992]]), achieving a best result of 4th at the 1988 Games in [[Seoul]] where he was the team captain. He was also a member of the [[Australia men's national basketball team|Boomers]] at the [[FIBA World Championship]]s in [[1978 FIBA World Championship|1978]], [[1982 FIBA World Championship|1982]], [[1986 FIBA World Championship|1986]], [[1990 FIBA World Championship|1990]] and [[1994 FIBA World Championship|1994]] with a best result of 5th place in both 1982 and 1994. At the [[Basketball at the 1984 Summer Olympics|1984 Los Angeles Olympic Games]], Smyth and his wife, [[Jenny Cheesman]], would become the first husband and wife to captain Australian teams at the same Olympics.<ref>[http://basketball.net.au/index.php?id=302&tx_ttnews%5Bpointer%5D=59&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=1323&tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=615&cHash=cfb495f2fb Back in the Day: Late Autumn 1984]. Basketball Australia News (May 18, 2010). Retrieved 2012-09-02.</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nAfter Adelaide 36ers coach Dave Claxton failed to take the team to the playoffs in 1997, the club hired the recently retired Smyth as head coach of the team from the [[1998 NBL season]], the club banking on his years of experience as a player despite his only previous coaching experience being as a specialist coach at the [[Australian Institute of Sport]] (AIS) during his playing days with Canberra as well as coaching [[South Adelaide Basketball Club|South Adelaide]] women's teams in the early 1980s.\n\nSmyth's impact on the club was immediate, with the 36ers winning both the 1998 and [[1998\u201399 NBL season|1998\u201399 NBL Championships]] in his first two seasons coaching in the league (according to Smyth, the 36ers coaching job in 1998 came down to himself and former North Melbourne and Brisbane coach [[Bruce Palmer (basketball)|Bruce Palmer]], but the 36ers ultimately wanted someone local). The team was beaten semi finalists for the next two seasons before winning their 4th championship, and 3rd under Smyth, in [[2001\u201302 NBL season|2001\u201302]]. Under his coaching the team would reach the elimination finals in [[2002\u201303 NBL season|2002\u201303]] and [[2003\u201304 NBL season|2003\u201304]] and improve to the quarters in [[2004-05 NBL season|2004-05]] and [[2005\u201306 NBL season|2005\u201306]] before failing to reach the playoffs twice which resulted in Smyth being replaced as head coach by former player and assistant Scott Ninnis.\n\nIn all, Phil Smyth coached the 36ers in the NBL for 365 games over 11 seasons, winning 205 games and losing 160.\n\nFollowing his stellar international career as a player and his championship success coaching the 36ers, Smyth was appointed head coach of the Boomers in January 2001. Unfortunately his international coaching career only lasted eight months. After losing the [[FIBA Oceania Championship 2001|2001 FIBA Oceania Championship]] to the [[New Zealand national basketball team|New Zealand Tall Blacks]] 1-2 the team failed to qualify for the [[2002 FIBA World Championship]] in [[Indianapolis]] as a result. It was the first time Australia had missed out on the [[FIBA World Championship]] since making their championship debut in [[1970 FIBA World Championship|1970]]. Smyth resigned from the job on 27 September 2001 and was ultimately replaced by the man who he defeated to win both the 1998 and 1998\u201399 NBL Championships, [[Brian Goorjian]].<ref>[http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-47178963.html HighBeam]{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n==Media work==\nIn March 2009 Smyth joined radio and sporting legend [[K. G. Cunningham]] to host an internet sports show KG and the General, streaming live from 3-6pm weekdays and podcast.\n\n==Honours==\nSmyth was made a Member of the [[Order of Australia]] in 1988, inducted into the [[Sport Australia Hall of Fame]] in 1997, and received an [[Australian Sports Medal]] in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=886440&search_type=quick&showInd=true|title=SMYTH, Philip John, AM|publisher=It's an Honour|accessdate=22 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sahof.org.au/hall-of-fame/member-profile/?memberID=208&memberType=athlete|title=Phil Smyth AM|publisher=Sport Australia Hall of Fame|accessdate=22 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=980599&search_type=quick&showInd=true|title=Smith, Phillip: Australian Sports Medal|publisher=It's an Honour|accessdate=22 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Honour roll ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- align=left\n| style=\"background:#efefef;\" | NBL career: \n| 1982\u20131995\n|-\n| style=\"background:#efefef;\" | Games: \n| 356 (StK 25, Can 282, Adl 33, Syd 16)\n|-\n| style=\"background:#efefef;\" | All-NBL First Team: \n| 6 (1982, 1983, 1984, 1985, 1988, 1989)\n|-\n| style=\"background:#efefef;\" | NBL best Defensive Player: \n| 4 (1982, 1983, 1988, 1989)\n|-\n|-align=left\n| style=\"background:#efefef;\" | NBL Grand Final appearances (player): \n| 5 (1983, 1984, 1988, 1989, 1994)\n|-\n| style=\"background:#efefef;\" |  NBL Championships (player): \n| 3 (1983, 1984, 1988)\n|-\n| style=\"background:#efefef;\" | NBL Grand Final MVP: \n| 1988\n|-\n|-align=left\n| style=\"background:#efefef;\" | NBL Grand Final appearances (coach): \n| 3 (1998, 1998/99, 2001/02)\n|-\n| style=\"background:#efefef;\" |  NBL Championships (coach): \n| 3 (1998, 1998/99, 2001/02)\n|-\n| style=\"background:#efefef;\" | NBL 20th Anniversary Team: \n| 1998\n|-\n| style=\"background:#efefef;\" | NBL 25th Anniversary Team: \n| 2003\n|}\n\n==NBL career stats==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| style=\"background:#afe6ba; width:3em;\"|\u2020\n|Denotes season(s) in which Smyth won an [[List of NBL champions|NBL championship]]\n|}\n\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| [[1982 NBL season|1982]]\n| style=\"text-align:l